{"id":"1402.4425","submitter":"Thomas Vojta","authors":"Hatem Barghathi and Thomas Vojta","title":"Phase Transitions on Random Lattices: How Random is Topological\n  Disorder?","comments":"4.5 pages, 4 eps figures, final version as published","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 113, 120602 (2014)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.113.120602","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the effects of topological (connectivity) disorder on phase\ntransitions. We identify a broad class of random lattices whose disorder\nfluctuations decay much faster with increasing length scale than those of\ngeneric random systems, yielding a wandering exponent of $\\omega=(d-1)/(2d)$ in\n$d$ dimensions. %instead of the generic value $\\omega=1/2$. The stability of\nclean critical points is thus governed by the criterion $(d+1)\\nu > 2$ rather\nthan the usual Harris criterion $d\\nu>2$, making topological disorder less\nrelevant than generic randomness. The Imry-Ma criterion is also modified,\nallowing first-order transitions to survive in all dimensions $d>1$. These\nresults explain a host of puzzling violations of the original criteria for\nequilibrium and nonequilibrium phase transitions on random lattices. We discuss\napplications, and we illustrate our theory by computer simulations of random\nVoronoi and other lattices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 Feb 2014 18:10:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 23 Sep 2014 16:17:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-09-24"}
